.TH AWK(1),User Commands,AWK(1)

.SH NAME
awk - pattern scanning and processing language

.SH SYNOPSIS
awk [OPTIONS] 'program' [FILE ...]
awk [OPTIONS] -f progfile [FILE ...]

.SH DESCRIPTION
The awk utility reads input line by line, splits each line into fields, and executes the specified program for each line. If no files are specified, awk reads from standard input.

Fields are accessed as $0 (entire line), $1 through $9 (individual fields). By default, fields are separated by whitespace.

.SH OPTIONS
-F fs: Use fs as the field separator. Supports \t for tab and \n for newline.

-f file: Read the program from file instead of the command line.

-h: Display help information and exit.

.SH PROGRAM SYNTAX
Programs are enclosed in braces. The following actions are supported:

{print}              Print entire line ($0)

{print $N}           Print field N (1-9)

{print $1, $2}       Print fields separated by space

{print $1 $2}        Print fields concatenated

{print NR}           Print record (line) number

{print NF}           Print number of fields

{print "text"}       Print literal string

Escape sequences in strings: \t for tab, \n for newline.

.SH EXIT STATUS
The awk utility exits 0 on success, and >0 if an error occurs.

.SH EXAMPLES
Print the first field of each line:

$ awk '{print $1}' file.txt

Print fields 1 and 3, colon-separated input:

$ awk -F: '{print $1, $3}' /etc/passwd

Number each line:

$ awk '{print NR, $0}' file.txt
